⁴⁶ Bacon regarded Induction as requisite both to give cleamess and precision to our notions and to establish true propositions which might serve as the basis of subsequent reasoning, whether inductive or deduc- tive. But, as we have already seen (note to Aph. 14), in order to realise or test the truth or adequacy of a notion, we must form at least one, and frequently a number ofjudgments. When we employ induction, therefore, ‘to elicit a notion,' we necessarily also employ it ‘to elicit an axiom,' and hence there is no real distinction between the process of induction or generalisation as applied to notions and as applied to judgments, propo· sitiens, oraxioms. .

⁴⁷ That is to say, it is Bacon’s Doctrine of Fallacies, and its fonction is to clear the mind of false notions, in order that it may be open to the reception of true ones. ·
